A film by @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

Directed by @caplice
Starring @nealpurchasejnr
Production Company @mojaveproductions

node.text:
Meet @stamba.hotel, the former Soviet printing factory located in downtown Tbilisi that has been reclaimed by a group of Georgian hospitality fanatics with the goal of putting their home town on the world stage of hospitality in a meaningful way.

If you are a little surprised to see a chic industrial loft hotel situated in the center of a former Soviet republic you are most certainly not alone, and that’s exactly what the Adjara hotel group consider to be their bread and butter: they live and breath to surprise potentially skeptic travelers with a hospitality experience that would rival that in any major city around the world.

Rooms are equipped with semi-professional La Marzocco coffee machines and McIntosh stereo units. Massive showers and brass bathtubs dominate the bathrooms, and original commissioned Georgian artworks adorn the concrete walls.

Part 1/2

Words and photos by @tedgushue for @type7

Shanghai isn't known for its dark skies but it is looking to the stars with this incredibly futuristic museum of Astronomy, which will be the biggest single space dedicated to educating the science of stargazing in the world. 

The project has been designed by @enneadarchitects to include as few right angles as possible and aims to embody the rational chaos of the universe in its form. The standout element is the planetarium, which floats almost weightlessly inside a dedicated atrium, and exposes itself to the skies above through the roof 🪐

Photos by @archexist
Words by @nat_twiss for @type7

node.text:
“I was on a crusade,” artist Edoardo Modenese (@theonlyedo) continues. “Like seven days a week for nine months, completing my first show just before the pandemic. It was a great experience because it was the first time I was actually working on my art every day. There’s a weird preconception that artists create art for the sake of it, but it’s much more of a business than that. You have to keep an eye on all the aspects of cost, maintenance, studio rent and website upkeep. Sometimes you can delegate the commercial side of things to a gallery or an agent, but first I wanted to see how far I could get myself with my own two hands.

Creating art to me is a total freedom of expression, finding your own language to communicate to the world whatever you want without closing yourself into a box. We’re in a world that’s so saturated with products and objects that I really wanted to make something that didn’t have any purpose or any function. My work kinda looks like it might be a product, so people sometimes see pieces of mine and go ‘oh is this a speaker?’ or they try to find a familiar function to contextualise it. But no, it’s just artwork.”

Photos by @lzrndr

node.text:
“Everyone tells you that you shouldn’t be doing art and that instead you should be thinking of doing something more lucrative,” Edoardo Modenese (@theonlyedo), the Milan-based artist explains. Edoardo has spent much of the last few years perfecting a style of artistic formwork’s from scratch. His connection art has spanned his entire life though like many of us, but the pressures of a commercialised world raised doubts about whether or not he could realistically make it happen. Enrolling half-heartedly on an industrial design degree, it was impressed upon him that form was worthless if it did not demonstrate functional and commercial viability, with aesthetic merit coming second. The dogma of it affirmed in Edoardo’s mind that to live a life fulfilled, he would have to resume the pursuit of art and commit to it completely. Speaking to @type7, he details some of the journey.

“I figured at first that I could adapt my creativity to design but I ended up hating what I was doing, I was simply not in a good place mentally. In that moment I was like ok the one thing that I know is art so I’m going to finish this degree and on the side I started working on new artwork. I graduated and decided still that design was not going to be my immediate career so I focused on even more artwork.”

Photos by @lzrndr
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Built in the mountains on New Zealand’s South Island, this triptych lakehouse was designed by AW (@awarchitects) to experience the great outdoors without neglecting on a few social responsibilities. The design won an award from the New Zealand Institute of Architects, which in itself is notable, but it’s made more interesting by the fact that the institute has recently been shifting its bar for entry, accounting for environmental impact among its prioritised criteria.

As of this year it’s now no longer possible to be recognised with an award from the NZIA without written statements detailing how a project’s construction methods, material choices and operational technologies impact the environment. Speaking to Type 7, chief architect Andrew Watson explains further:

“This year’s criteria really demanded a lot more depth and thought,” he explained to us recently. “There was a marked shift to smaller design using tangible sustainable design principles. I think this will have a good impact on how architects develop future projects and the NZIA is to be commended for this industry lead push.” With a minimal ecological footprint and sweeping views, the Lake House is setting a new standard of what can be achieved in nature while still being respectful of it.

Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7 
Photos via @awarchitects

node.text:
In the process of restoring this Richard Neutra-designed house in Los Angeles, Hiroki Nakamura (@visvimwmv) insisted that no “new” modern materials were used. Instead the exact same fixtures originally put into the building were sourced and installed. 

Ultimately an office, a kitchen, a living room and an unsightly air-conditioning unit were removed in the complete overhaul of the home. Cabinets, sofas, wood paneling, carpets, and original Formica countertops were compassionately restored using the same materials that would have been used back in 1951.

Mr. Nakamura says that by resurrecting the original design as precisely as possible he could unlock the message that Neutra had embedded into his design.

The house now stands as a testament to both Neutra’s original intention and Mr. Nakamura’s own vision and artistry. It’s the celebration of a message sent out by an architect in 1951 which was then received, restored, and appreciated by a designer today.  

Photos and words by @benbertucci for @type7

node.text:
Hiroki Nakamura’s clothing company @visvimwmv is renowned for its exquisite attention to detail and careful sourcing of materials which harken back to methods and techniques used before mass factory production was the norm. This house, located just off Mulholland Drive in Los Angeles, has been cared for and restored with the same philosophy.

The “Schaarman House” was designed by Austrian architect Richard Neutra in 1951 when Neutra was at the height of his American period which coincided with the architectural era known as “California Modern Living”. By the time Mr. Nakamura purchased the property in 2017, it had fallen victim to renovations that left it almost unrecognisable to Neutra’s original vision.

Mr. Nakamura has restored the house to its original form with the assistance of two Neutra experts who referred directly to the original blueprints and designs as well as communications between Neutra, his client Mr. Schaarman, and the foreman on site in 1951.

Photos and words by @benbertucci for @type7

node.text:
Built in the forest of Costa Rica, this treehouse is a bit of a departure from the work we’re used to seeing from Olson Kundig (@olsonkundig). The Seattle based studio tends to work in the colder regions of rural North America, having cultivated a style that suits it very well. Little of that is present in this more tropical commission, though that hasn’t stopped them from producing magic.

The clients are surfers, so the top floor of the house is designed as a lookout spot perched above the trees where there’s a clear view of the beach. From there they can gauge whether or not it’s worth a day on the water. When it isn’t, the house is hardly a rough second choice. Warm, open and wholly organic throughout, it’s a far cry from the hard, industrial designs we’re used to from OK.

Teak makes up the majority of the woodwork. The self oiling hardwood is perfect for exterior construction and it grows locally, so very little of the building’s mass has had to travel very far. Even the pillars inside are tree trunks, lightly refinished but in keeping with their natural form. Sure it’s a departure from their regular schedule, but it’s a knock out piece none the less.

Photos by Nic Lehoux
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7
